postcontent:
Benchmade's 6800 SBK Limited Production #104 of 400 that is new in the box. Provides an Ambidextrous Push Button (APB) release button, with a spine-mounted safety, which prevents unintended deployment. The 6800SBK (APB) employs a black coated 154-CM stainless steel blade (serrated) and black anodized 6061-T6 aluminum handle with stainless steel liners and a carbide tipped glass breaker on the end of the handle. $195 is the best price for this knife anywhere on the net. Also have the ultimate Survival Knife:

Kershaw Survival knife system with saw tooth back on the blade, Model 1005. Trade Value $300. Cash $275.
NIB Benchmade Auto APB 6800SBK for $275 trade or $240 cash.

It is 12-5/8" overall, is in mint condition with original sheath and all accessories. The blade is as new with a few rub marks showing up in the matt finish. It comes with a full-size Brunton compass and all the original survival gear. Very well done and my favorite of the factory hollow handle survival knives from the 1980's.

Knife is at least 26 years old and a unique piece of Kershaw history. Everything is in excellent or better condition, including the knife and sheath. This is a great and I mean really great building block for an outstanding survival knife system. The sheath is almost as important as the knife because of all the pockets and heavy-duty grommets built in to it help you organize, protect and carry your gear.

It was rated number three in a review of survival knives in the world back in the late 80's, but I do not remember the magazine or the other knives in the review. They were last made in about 1989. That makes this knife at least 26 years old and a unique piece of Kershaw history.

The last time I saw one this good was about 9 years ago, and it sold for $350.

The following is from the 1989 Kershaw catalog:  

Kershaw's fixed-blade Survival Knife provides and added measure of safety in a multi-purpose knife designed for situations in the forest, outback, tundra, or anywhere a big knife for tough jobs can make the difference. It combines the sought-after features you need in a functional, durable knife.

Its machete-shaped survival blade is made of Kershaw's AUS 8-A high-carbon stainless steel, sandblasted to a smooth non-reflective finish, and shaped with strong tang to assure a solid lock-up between the blade and the handle. Double cross-cut saw teeth on the back can saw through tough jobs such as wood, bone, and even metal.

The handle itself is a steel pipe covered with Kershaw's Task Force™ polymer rubber grip, which is contoured with finger grooves for positive control. The Task Force handle provides a solid non-slip grip in all conditions. The butt can be used as a hammer without damaging the knife. Its threaded butt cap features "O" rings to seal a water-tight storage tubing in the handle, which can store emergency items, such as matches and fishing hooks and line.

The oversized Cordura sheath provides two storage compartments, one for a full size compass and waterproof survival cards, which are included. This heavy duty sheath features wide loops for use with belt or leg straps, a fold down strap with quick-release clasp, and heavy-duty grommets.

title: For Sale:  DL 44 Han Solo Blaster (7.63 x 25mm)
postcontent:
DL 44 Heavy Blaster - Han Solo / A New Hope Version

NOTE: THIS IS A REAL FIREARM, NOT A TOY OR NON-FIRING REPLICA.

This is a custom, all-metal, fully functional, firing DL 44 Blaster nearly identical to the one used by Han Solo in the original Star Wars movie (A New Hope). It, like the movie version, began as a vintage 7.63 "Broomhandle" C96 Mauser. The upper and lower receivers are from two different vintage C96's. The grips are original to the weapon. Over 40 hours of work went into the production of this weapon. The firing pin and recoil spring have been replaced with new ones. It has been blued, the other parts chemically blackened and then distressed/battle-worn (complete with "mystery disk" on the left side of the magazine housing). A permanently mounted bull barrel sleeve has been installed. Scope mount studs have been welded to the receiver. A limited edition, all-metal parts kit has been used to complete the build. The scope is hollow, with brass and glass fittings, but is non-magnifying and has no internal reticle. The blaster has no sight greeblies attached to the top of the bull barrel (Star Wars guys will understand that). There is enough photographic evidence (in my opinion) that they were not present during much of filming, so I did not add any. I said that it was "nearly identical" earlier in the description, and I said that because the lanyard attachment point on this grip is set at a different angle than the screen-used version. Other than that, it's spot on.

Being a real weapon, it will only be sold to adults. If shipping is required, it will only be shipped to an FFL holder (shipping is flat $25 via UPS only to contiguous US).

This weapon is fully-firing and functions perfectly using standard 7.63 x 25mm Mauser rounds (also known as 30 Mauser).

Serious inquiries only. No trades. 

"Hokey religions and ancient weapons are no match for a good blaster at your side, kid."

postcontent:
I have a 1958 Bernardelli-Gardone V.T. Italia- Cal 6.35 BRE. VP (Vest Pocket). This is an older well made Italian Semi-Auto 25 ACP in Good Condition. Gun functions perfectly and is a nice little piece for a collection. I have the original box and paperwork from December1958 including the first original bill of sale to the original purchaser in 1959

 Bernardelli entered into the gun business in 1631 first making barrels in Gardone Val Trompia, Brescia Italy. In 1865 Vincenzo Bernardelli founded the company which still exist today. In the 1920's Bernardelli also manufactured componets for Alfa Romeo aircraft engines. In the 1930's they made an Italian service revolver know as the System Bodeo, Model 1889. They are also known for crafting very high-end shotguns. After World War II, Bernardelli introduced its first self-loading pistol, the VP (Vest Pocket) Model, which was based on the Walther Model 9.

 The Bernardelli VP is a very small blowback-operated striker-fired .25 caliber (6.35 mm) pistol with a barbell-shaped takedown latch at the rear. It has a full length slide that covers the 2" barrel, with an external extractor on the right side, an internal connector on the left side; a 5 shot magazine that incorporates a magazine safety.
